piritual directors, alms collectors, educators, scholars, and sponsors of charitable works. Each order brought to this work a distinct identity that informed people's beliefs and shaped variations in the practice of Catholicism. Contrary to prevailing views, mendicant orders flourished during the seventeenth and early eighteenth centuries, and even the eighteenth-century reforms that ended this era were not as devastating as has been assumed.Even in the face of new institutional challenges, the demand for their services continued through the end of the colonial period, demonstrating the continued vitality of baroque piety.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aColonial citieszMexicoxHistoryy16th century. 0aColonial citieszMexicoxHistoryy17th century. 0aColonial citieszMexicoxHistoryy18th century. 0aFriarszMexicoxHistoryy16th century. 0aFriarszMexicoxHistoryy17th century. 0aFriarszMexicoxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804783255zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804783255423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804783255.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles